<rdf:RDF xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#"
    xmlns:cr="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#"
    xmlns:dpo="http://www.daml.org/2001/03/daml+oil#"
    xmlns:log="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/log#"
    xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
    xmlns:s="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
    xmlns:string="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/string#">

    <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#CanEncrypt">
        <s:comment>PublicKeyObjects which are cabable of encrypting things</s:comment>
        <s:isSubClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#PublicKeyObject"/>
    </rdf:Description>

    <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#CanSign">
        <s:comment>PublicKeyObjects which are cabable of signing things.
True if the algorithm is capable of signing data; returns false otherwise.
To test if a given key object can sign data, use CanSign and HasPrivate. </s:comment>
        <s:isSubClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#PublicKeyObject"/>
    </rdf:Description>

    <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#HasPrivate">
        <s:comment>
Some keys have private parts, some don't.  This is the class of those which do.
</s:comment>
        <s:isSubClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#PublicKeyObject"/>
    </rdf:Description>

    <s:Class rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#HashFunction">
        <s:comment>
The crypographic hash functions are (being functions) unique and 
(the whole point of being hash functions) are, when secure, assumed
unambiguous. That is, you have the right hash you ahve the right document.
Currently (2001/9)only SHA is given that property.
</s:comment>
        <s:label>Any crypographic hash function</s:label>
    </s:Class>

    <s:Class rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#PublicKeyObject">
        <s:comment>An object corresponding to a key for some algorithm.
    The object can hold a private and optionally a private key.</s:comment>
    </s:Class>

    <dpo:UniqueProperty rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#md5">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#Property"/>
        <s:comment>The object is a MD5 hash of the subject.</s:comment>
        <s:domain rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/string#String"/>
        <s:label>MD5 hash</s:label>
        <s:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/string#String"/>
    </dpo:UniqueProperty>

    <s:Property rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#publicKey">
        <s:comment>The object is a public key object that doesn't
    contain the private key data in the subject.
    This function extracts the public part.</s:comment>
        <s:domain rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#PublicKeyObject"/>
        <s:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#PublicKeyObject"/>
    </s:Property>

    <dpo:UnambiguousProperty rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#sha">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.daml.org/2001/03/daml+oil#UniqueProperty"/>
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#Property"/>
        <s:comment>The object is a SHA-1 hash of the subject.</s:comment>
        <s:domain rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/string#String"/>
        <s:label>SHA hash</s:label>
        <s:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/string#String"/>
    </dpo:UnambiguousProperty>

    <rdf:Property rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#sign">
        <s:comment>The subject should be a list of two things,
a hash string and a key (containing private and public parts).
The obejcts is calculated as a signature string by signing
the has with the key's private part.</s:comment>
        <s:label>sign</s:label>
    </rdf:Property>

    <rdf:Property rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#verify">
        <s:comment>If the subject is a key object containing
private and public parts and the obejct is a list of
a hash and a signature, then this is true iff the signaure is
a valid signatre of the hash with the key.</s:comment>
    </rdf:Property>

    <rdf:Property rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/crypto#verifyBoolean">
        <s:comment>If the subject is a list
containg the keypair, a hash and a signature
then the object is either "1" if the signature validates
or "0" is it does not.</s:comment>
    </rdf:Property>
</rdf:RDF>
